data.meta_desc: During WW2 Digvijaysinhji Ranjitsinhji the Maharaja of Nawanagar India adopted over a 1000 Polish children after their release from the Soviet orphanage in 1942. Jam Saheb On their arrival to his kingdom The maharaja greeted the children with the words "You are no longer orphans. From now on you are Nawanagarians and I am bapu your father father to all Nawanagarians." The maharaja built dormitories in which each child had his or her own bed and provided then with food, clothes and medical care. He also provided for the children's education by bringing in Polish teahcers. In an interview to tge weekly magazine Poland, Jam Saheb explained why he had offered to provide shelter: "I am trying to do whatever I can to save the children; as they must regain their health and strength after these dreadful trails, so that in the future they will be able to cope with the tasks that await them in a liberated Poland." After the political turn of 1989, a sqaure in Warsaw was named after him. Since 2012, a small park in the city's south-western area of Ochota has been called the Sqaure of the Good Maharaja. A monument dedicated to the kind-hearted king was also erected, and he was posthumously awarded the Commander's Cross of the Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland.. India,Poland.  Memes.

Jam Saheb On their arrival to his kingdom The maharaja greeted the children with the words "You are no longer orphans. From now on you are Nawanagarians and I am bapu your father father to all Nawanagarians." The maharaja built dormitories in which each child had his or her own bed and provided then with food, clothes and medical care. He also provided for the children's education by bringing in Polish teahcers. In an interview to tge weekly magazine Poland, Jam Saheb explained why he had offered to provide shelter: "I am trying to do whatever I can to save the children; as they must regain their health and strength after these dreadful trails, so that in the future they will be able to cope with the tasks that await them in a liberated Poland." After the political turn of 1989, a sqaure in Warsaw was named after him. Since 2012, a small park in the city's south-western area of Ochota has been called the Sqaure of the Good Maharaja.
